{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493315","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493315"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:05:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:05:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1282"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1282","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1282"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.54,0.32,0.09,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1282"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54727"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1282","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1282"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1282"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40258"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"691"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4340"},{"type":"tags","id":"4400"},{"type":"tags","id":"4401"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12799"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1354"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15423"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17471"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43070"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54727","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54727"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the Antenatal clinic at 36 weeks gestation. This is her second pregnancy. She had an emergency lower uterine segment caesarean section two years ago for fetal distress at 7 cm dilatation. She was not aware of any complications with her previous caesarean and she was counselled that she would be a candidate for a vaginal birth after caesarean section following her first delivery. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She has expressed her preference for a vaginal delivery this time and requires counselling about the risks and benefits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the reported incidence of uterine rupture in a spontaneous labourer following a previous lower uterine segment caesarean section?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["1 in 20","1 in 200","1 in 2000","1 in 20000","1 in 100000"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is considering a vaginal birth after caesarean (VBAC). The reported incidence of uterine rupture in spontaneous labour following a previous lower uterine segment caesarean section is \u003Cstrong\u003E1 in 200\u003C/strong\u003E (0.5%). This risk increases to about 1% when labour is induced.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E1 in 20\u003C/strong\u003E (5%) is much higher than the actual risk and would likely discourage most women from attempting VBAC if it were true. This high risk is not supported by current evidence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E1 in 2000\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003E1 in 20000\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003E1 in 100000\u003C/strong\u003E are all significantly lower than the actual risk. While these lower risks might be more reassuring to patients, they do not accurately represent the true risk of uterine rupture in VBAC.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen counselling a patient about VBAC, it\u0027s important to discuss both risks and benefits. Benefits of VBAC include a shorter hospital stay, quicker recovery, and improved chances of successful vaginal delivery in future pregnancies. It also allows the patient to avoid the risks associated with repeat caesarean sections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther risks of VBAC, besides uterine rupture, include a 30% chance of requiring a non-elective caesarean section, risk of third or fourth-degree perineal tear, and a 1 in 500 risk of hysterectomy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe success rates for VBAC are highest in women who have previously had a vaginal birth and those who present in established spontaneous labour. The lowest success rates are in women who have previously had a failed instrumental delivery or obstructed labour. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that the risk of uterine rupture is significantly higher in women who have had a classical caesarean section (vertical incision on the upper uterus) compared to those who have had a lower segment caesarean section. The risk of uterine rupture after a classical caesarean is estimated to be 4-9%, which is why VBAC is generally not recommended for these women.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis information should be part of the counselling process to help the patient make an informed decision about her preferred mode of delivery.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vaginal birth after caesarean (VBAC) has a low risk of uterine rupture, approximately 1 in 200 for spontaneous labour.","The risk of uterine rupture in VBAC increases to about 1% when labour is induced.","Success rates for VBAC are highest in women who have previously had a vaginal birth and those who present in established spontaneous labour.","The risk of uterine rupture is significantly higher after a classical caesarean section compared to a lower segment caesarean section."],"references":["RCOG Green-top Clinical Guideline Birth after Previous Caesarean Birth. www.rcog.org.uk/ en/guidelines-research-services/guidelines/gtg45. Accessed 9/2/21"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40258"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1282"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40258","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40258"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-09T16:34:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-09T16:35:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1282"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54727"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"691","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/691"},"attr